    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-06-08T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-06-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="764"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d764">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">702.022/6–851</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The First Secretary of Embassy in Argentina</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Martindale</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Buenos Aires</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-06-08">June 8,
                            1951</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">No. 1923</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">Subject: Argentine Reply to British Protest Concerning Antarctic
                        Bases.<note n="1" xml:id="d764fn1">Despatch 1753, from Buenos Aires, May 10,
                        not printed, had reported that the British Embassy had formally protested
                        against the establishment of two more Argentine bases in Antarctica (735.00
                        (W)/5–1051).</note>
                </p>
                <p>The Foreign Minister<note n="2" xml:id="d764fn2">Argentine Foreign Minister Dr.
                        Hipolito J. Paz.</note> received the press on June 7 and issued copies of
                    the note handed British Embassy June 1<note n="3" xml:id="d764fn3">The text of
                        the note was enclosed with despatch 1977, from Buenos Aires, June 18, not
                        printed.</note> rejecting the British protest against Argentine bases
                    established in Antarctica. (Clippings from <hi rend="italic">La Nación</hi>,
                    June 8, <hi rend="italic">Democracia</hi>, June 8 and <hi rend="italic">La
                        Epoca</hi>, June 7, enclosed.)<note n="4" xml:id="d764fn4">Not
                        printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The Peronista press headlines the government’s strong nationalist stand and
                    reassertion of Argentine sovereignty.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert</hi> G. <hi rend="smallcaps">Martindale</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
